spanGrp.span: ‘A man lived with his wife up far in the woods.
Tara jeyiwa je sẽr-gẽ í juape ra ke mapumĩ jui kã' diginã
Their house was made of leaves.
ta jie-wa jũ yu-lë rö kagu wa
But one day there came a time when they had a child, a boy child.
Tara un dia tara jie-wa se-nã' demĩũ un tiempo tara jeska jie-wa yaba ta jie-wa yaba e-gla rö jeyiwa…
They talk about how the child would grow up and work;
jeska jie-wa tsõ kãpagö í yaba í yaba kebir-mĩ yaba dö-mĩ keyege ra jirö kenẽ'wẽ-mĩ-ite
they lived well but they said, the man said to the woman,
Tara jie-wa sẽr-gẽ böi tara jie-wa të shá-nẽ í jeyiyi í shá í alaglö ĩã
“let’s go far, let´s walk around the house!
But let´s leave the child sleeping at home.
Tara se të yaba mẽtanã jũ nã köpö
We will come back in when he wakes up.”
Tara í shkináũ-te-ra se bötö-nẽ í sũã'”
They went away and left the child at home.
They were in the forest and did not see that some deer came in the house and took the child along.
Jie-wa kajalali kã' diginã ka të í sunẽ-ra mãĩ due yabla de-wã jũ nã Je të… í yaba mẽnẽu-mĩ/ mẽnẽtse-mĩ… mẽnẽtse-mĩ
The child chased those deer well into the woods.
yaba të je due yabla töjiá-mĩ töjiá-mĩ kal diginã kal diginã mapumĩ
the deer went away under the trees and left him alone.
(_) je due yabla mẽnẽu-lo-mĩ kal diginã të mã'tanã eglauña
There a huge snake grabbed him, rolled him up;
tara jeska mãga kebé tã'ĩ të í gugá-wã të í pabutrá-wã
child thought it was his mother or his father.
Tara ee… yaba të í begetsá rö mina o í kaga yaba… í kaga
jeska ñẽ (m) (_) kebé ra jinõ Yaba jinã'
talked to it and caressed it.
yaba ktá kebé ra yaba të due ee/ kebé pasigá
The snake threw the child down; so the child lied down and cried;
yaba yaba jiá-wã-nẽ je kebé të ra ka yaba jiñá/ (_) jẽk baglá-wã jiñã'
the snake climbed up a tree, and because the child was crying so much, it came down and caressed him.
Tara jeskara kebé kebé mẽnẽka kaljula nã y komo yaba jiñõ-gẽ (m) tã'ĩ kebé jẽk jiá-te-nẽ kebé të í pasigá
Then his mother, the adults came back home and did not find the child; he was not sleeping.
Tara í mina í keglö-wa deu-lo-nẽ Jeskara jũ nã nẽ të ka yaba konẽ të yaba yaba (_) yaba ka kunã köpö
His father looked for him under the trees and things.
yaba je yule-gẽ kaga të (m) í yulá kal diginã jirö diginã
He fought with the creatures, the wild dogs from the woods.
Bichi-wa ra nã kbá chichi tsõ kã' diginã je-wa (m) ra í nã kbá
But he did not find the child.
Tara yaba të mãĩ oso dolonã kwã'
he thought it was his father; the child went away with the creature.
begetsá-ite í kaga të/ í kaga mẽnẽu-mĩ yaba mẽnẽu-mĩ (_) bichi ra
His father and mother looked for him but did not find him.
Tara í mina-wa í kaga-wa të í yulá ka í konẽ
Í yule-mĩ-nẽ í kaga-wa ktá-nẽ ñara ke
“the child got lost; let’s let him there!”
“í shenã'-wã shenã'-wã se wã í jöatanã” (m)
